<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Claim Types</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Sexual harassment is a form of sex discrimination prohibited by Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964
    (42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-2(a)). Federal courts and the EEOC recognize two primary theories &mdash; quid pro quo and hostile work
    environment &mdash; plus a related retaliation claim that often becomes the strongest part of a case after the plaintiff complains.
    The categories matter because the elements, the available defenses, and the practical settlement value differ.
  </p>

  <h2>Quid pro quo harassment</h2>
  <p>
    Latin for &ldquo;this for that.&rdquo; A supervisor or anyone with authority over employment conditions explicitly or implicitly
    conditions a job benefit on the employee&rsquo;s submission to sexual conduct, or punishes the employee for refusing. The Supreme
    Court formally recognized this theory in <em>Meritor Savings Bank, FSB v. Vinson</em>, 477 U.S. 57 (1986).
  </p>
  <p>The plaintiff must show:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Membership in a protected class (sex; the statute is sex-neutral in practice).</li>
    <li>Unwelcome sexual advances or conduct.</li>
    <li>The conduct was tied to a tangible employment action (hiring, firing, promotion, demotion, reassignment, significant pay change, benefits).</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    When a supervisor takes a tangible employment action, the employer is <strong>vicariously liable as a matter of law</strong> under
    <em>Burlington Industries, Inc. v. Ellerth</em>, 524 U.S. 742 (1998), and the <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> affirmative defense
    is unavailable. That is why quid pro quo cases with a documented tangible action are among the highest-value harassment claims.
  </p>

  <h2>Hostile work environment harassment</h2>
  <p>
    Unwelcome sex-based conduct sufficiently severe or pervasive to alter the conditions of the victim&rsquo;s employment and create
    an abusive working environment. The controlling federal standard comes from <em>Harris v. Forklift Systems, Inc.</em>, 510 U.S. 17 (1993):
    the conduct must be objectively hostile (a reasonable person would find it abusive) and subjectively hostile (the plaintiff did find it abusive).
  </p>
  <p>Courts weigh:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Frequency of the conduct.</li>
    <li>Severity.</li>
    <li>Whether physically threatening or humiliating, or a mere offensive utterance.</li>
    <li>Whether it unreasonably interferes with work performance.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A <strong>single severe incident</strong> (sexual assault, for example) can satisfy the standard without any pattern. Most
    hostile-environment cases rely on a course of conduct, and contemporaneous documentation matters enormously: dates, locations,
    witnesses, and what was said or done in each instance.
  </p>

  <h2>The Faragher/Ellerth affirmative defense</h2>
  <p>
    When a supervisor creates a hostile environment but takes <em>no</em> tangible employment action, the employer can raise an
    affirmative defense under <em>Faragher v. City of Boca Raton</em>, 524 U.S. 775 (1998), and <em>Ellerth</em>. To prevail the
    employer must prove both prongs by a preponderance:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>The employer exercised reasonable care to prevent and promptly correct sexually harassing behavior (typically: a published, distributed anti-harassment policy with a complaint procedure, training, and prompt investigation of complaints).</li>
    <li>The plaintiff unreasonably failed to take advantage of preventive or corrective opportunities, or to otherwise avoid harm.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The defense fails entirely if there was a tangible action. It also fails if the complaint procedure routes complaints through
    the harasser, was not communicated to employees, or was demonstrably ineffective in prior cases. For coworker (non-supervisor)
    harassment, the standard is negligence: the employer is liable only if it knew or should have known of the harassment and
    failed to take prompt remedial action.
  </p>

  <h2>Retaliation claims</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII&rsquo;s anti-retaliation provision, 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3(a), prohibits employers from punishing employees for
    opposing unlawful conduct or participating in EEOC proceedings. The standard for an actionable adverse action is broader than
    the underlying discrimination standard: it includes <em>any</em> action a reasonable employee would find materially adverse,
    meaning it might dissuade a reasonable worker from making or supporting a charge (<em>Burlington N. &amp; Santa Fe Ry. v. White</em>,
    548 U.S. 53 (2006)).
  </p>
  <p>
    Retaliation often becomes the centerpiece of a sexual harassment case, for three reasons:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The plaintiff does not need to win the underlying harassment claim to win retaliation &mdash; only a reasonable, good-faith belief in unlawful conduct.</li>
    <li>The temporal proximity between complaint and adverse action is usually well-documented.</li>
    <li>Juries reliably punish post-complaint retaliation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Retaliation is also fully subject to the same Title VII damages structure, including the &sect; 1981a(b)(3) employer-size cap on
    combined compensatory and punitive damages.
  </p>

  <h2>Same-sex harassment</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII covers harassment between members of the same sex. The Supreme Court resolved a circuit split in
    <em>Oncale v. Sundowner Offshore Services, Inc.</em>, 523 U.S. 75 (1998), holding that sex-based harassment is actionable
    regardless of the sex of the harasser or the victim, provided the conduct was &ldquo;because of sex.&rdquo; The plaintiff can show
    that through evidence of sexual desire, general hostility to one sex in the workplace, or comparative evidence that the harasser
    treated members of one sex worse than the other in a mixed-sex workplace.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Court&rsquo;s decision in <em>Bostock v. Clayton County</em>, 590 U.S. 644 (2020), confirmed that Title VII&rsquo;s prohibition
    on sex discrimination includes discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, which folds in harassment claims
    by LGBTQ employees on the same legal footing.
  </p>

  <h2>Third-party harassment liability</h2>
  <p>
    Employers can be liable for harassment by non-employees &mdash; customers, vendors, clients, patients &mdash; when the employer
    knew or should have known of the harassment and failed to take prompt, appropriate remedial action within its control.
    EEOC guidance and 29 C.F.R. &sect; 1604.11(e) recognize this category. Examples include restaurant servers harassed by regular
    patrons, healthcare staff harassed by patients, and field-sales employees harassed by customer-site personnel. The employer&rsquo;s
    available remedies are narrower (it cannot fire a customer&rsquo;s employee) but the duty to investigate and to act on its
    own side of the relationship remains.
  </p>

  <h2>How to figure out which theory fits your facts</h2>
  <p>
    Most plaintiffs plead more than one theory. If a supervisor demanded sex and you were demoted, you have quid pro quo plus
    likely hostile environment plus likely retaliation if you complained first. If coworkers ran a daily campaign of unwelcome
    comments and the company knew, you have hostile environment with negligence liability. The intake call with an employment
    plaintiff&rsquo;s attorney usually maps the theories in fifteen minutes; bring the timeline and the documents.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
